docs.abstract: The university is committing $100 million for an endowed “Legacy of Slavery Fund.” Its report carefully avoided treading on direct financial reparations for descendants of enslaved people.
docs.snippet: The university is committing $100 million for an endowed “Legacy of Slavery Fund.” Its report carefully avoided treading on direct financial reparations for descendants of enslaved people.
docs.lead_paragraph: In one column are the names of more than 70 enslaved people at Harvard: Venus, Juba, Cesar, Cicely. They are only first names, or sometimes no name at all — “the Moor” or “a little boy” — of people and stories that have been all but forgotten.

headline.main: Harvard Details Its Ties to Slavery and Its Plans for Redress

docs.abstract: The Aldrich Contemporary Art Museum looks back at a 1971 exhibition devoted to women and puts their work in conversation with emerging feminist artists.
docs.snippet: The Aldrich Contemporary Art Museum looks back at a 1971 exhibition devoted to women and puts their work in conversation with emerging feminist artists.
docs.lead_paragraph: When “Twenty Six Contemporary Women Artists” opened in 1971 at the Aldrich Contemporary Art Museum in Ridgefield, Conn., it was the first exhibition of its kind in this country, organized by the feminist art critic Lucy R. Lippard as a direct response to the vast underrepresentation of female artists in museums and galleries. It spawned a wave of similar all-women shows throughout the 1970s.

headline.main: Revisiting a Groundbreaking Show of Feminist Art

docs.abstract: Novels from Ali Smith, Jean Hanff Korelitz and Mieko Kawakami; a debut Y.A. romance by Casey McQuiston; a sequel to Elif Batuman’s “The Idiot” and much more.
docs.snippet: Novels from Ali Smith, Jean Hanff Korelitz and Mieko Kawakami; a debut Y.A. romance by Casey McQuiston; a sequel to Elif Batuman’s “The Idiot” and much more.
docs.lead_paragraph: Kawakami, already celebrated in Japan, has built a following among English readers for her earlier novels about the lives of women, “Breasts and Eggs” and “Heaven.” Here she focuses on a shy proofreader who is coaxed out of her solitude by a physics teacher — andconfronts unsettling episodes from her past.
